00:14:40.680 --> 00:14:42.800
on the commodity market,
which is mainly what comes

00:14:42.800 --> 00:14:47.170
from West Africa, is sold for
less than a dollar a kilo.

00:14:47.170 --> 00:14:50.310
Which means that the workers
in those places that grow

00:14:50.310 --> 00:14:52.510
that chocolate and
is their livelihood,

00:14:52.510 --> 00:14:55.020
they're getting paid
pennies a day, sometimes less

00:14:55.020 --> 00:14:56.320
in some circumstances.

00:14:56.320 --> 00:14:59.970
So that's part of why we have
a commitment to direct trade

00:14:59.970 --> 00:15:02.170
and to paying more
for our chocolate

00:15:02.170 --> 00:15:03.960
and paying the farmers directly.

00:15:03.960 --> 00:15:06.900
When there's no middleman, when
you're avoiding all that stuff,

00:15:06.900 --> 00:15:08.930
the farmers get the
money that they deserve

00:15:08.930 --> 00:15:12.780
and there's no one along the
line taking money from them.

00:15:12.780 --> 00:15:14.930
Which is also really important.

00:15:14.930 --> 00:15:17.680
And one of the things that
we have a strong connection

00:15:17.680 --> 00:15:21.330
to Brazil, not just
because Sam is from there,

00:15:21.330 --> 00:15:26.110
but because Brazil, after
the witches broom blight,

00:15:26.110 --> 00:15:29.390
it took about a decade
for Brazil to recover.

00:15:29.390 --> 00:15:32.690
And CCN 51, which Sam mentioned,

00:15:32.690 --> 00:15:37.880
was a sort of life-saving
breed of cacao for Brazil.

00:15:37.880 --> 00:15:41.450
It however does not
have great taste.

00:15:41.450 --> 00:15:45.540
And in the scramble to
recover from the disease,

00:15:45.540 --> 00:15:49.400
a lot of CCN 51 was just
indiscriminately planted

00:15:49.400 --> 00:15:51.700
and bred into other
breeds of cacao.

00:15:51.700 --> 00:15:54.830
And Brazil, unfortunately,
got this terrible reputation

00:15:54.830 --> 00:15:57.970
for having less than
high-quality cocoa.

00:15:57.970 --> 00:16:02.870
And most of its cocoa even to
this day is sold internally.

00:16:02.870 --> 00:16:06.330
Brazil has a huge
demand internally

00:16:06.330 --> 00:16:08.660
for chocolate and for cocoa.

00:16:08.660 --> 00:16:11.010
And so very little
of it is exported.

00:16:11.010 --> 00:16:14.940
That's actually been one of our
biggest challenges is we have

00:16:14.940 --> 00:16:19.540
to import it ourselves to
get it here from Brazil.

00:16:19.540 --> 00:16:21.400
And there's some
regions in South America

00:16:21.400 --> 00:16:25.740
where they have larger
cooperatives and larger sort

00:16:25.740 --> 00:16:28.150
of companies that are
doing the exportation

00:16:28.150 --> 00:16:30.750
and you can get better
access to it here

00:16:30.750 --> 00:16:34.260
in the States, but
not in Brazil.

00:16:34.260 --> 00:16:37.200
So one of the things that is
one of our focuses is going

00:16:37.200 --> 00:16:40.390
to our farms and helping
them expand outside

00:16:40.390 --> 00:16:45.260
of the Brazilian market, and
not only that but bringing back

00:16:45.260 --> 00:16:48.310
from Brazil cocoa that
is really great quality

00:16:48.310 --> 00:16:50.170
and has really nice flavor.

00:16:50.170 --> 00:16:53.010
And trying to sort of show the
industry and show the world

00:16:53.010 --> 00:16:55.350
that like, hey, Brazil
has amazing cocoa.

00:16:55.350 --> 00:16:57.570
It's not all CCN 51.

00:16:57.570 --> 00:17:02.240
CCN 51 saved the
industry, but now, you know,

00:17:02.240 --> 00:17:04.690
those genetics are there
and there's all this fine

00:17:04.690 --> 00:17:07.530
and heritage cocoa that's
coming back in Brazil.

00:17:07.530 --> 00:17:10.770
And that's sort of what we're
trying to do and we're trying

00:17:10.770 --> 00:17:12.590
to do with our chocolate
and make sure

00:17:12.590 --> 00:17:15.070
that we make it really good.

00:17:15.070 --> 00:17:18.100
So that we can say like, hey,
everybody should take interest

00:17:18.100 --> 00:17:22.680
in Brazil and kind of try and
revitalize this lost economy

00:17:22.680 --> 00:17:26.800
that occurred by just a
terrible natural disaster there.

00:17:26.800 --> 00:17:30.170
And so I'm going to start
flipping through some pictures

00:17:30.170 --> 00:17:34.030
that sort of talk
about our sourcing.

00:17:34.030 --> 00:17:38.090
This a picture of cacao
pods right before harvest.

00:17:38.090 --> 00:17:40.250
These have been cut
down from the tree.

00:17:40.250 --> 00:17:46.430
You can see, they're beautiful
after they are cut open.

00:17:46.430 --> 00:17:49.170
This is sort of talking
about what sort

00:17:49.170 --> 00:17:50.470
of Sam also already covered,

00:17:50.470 --> 00:17:52.950
what we look for
in our sourcing.

00:17:52.950 --> 00:17:54.250
We look for quality.

00:17:54.250 --> 00:17:58.880
We look for the environmental
practices of agroforestry.

00:17:58.880 --> 00:18:02.800
Part of what improves the
quality of cacao is growing it

00:18:02.800 --> 00:18:04.100
in a diverse environment.

00:18:04.100 --> 00:18:09.160
Cacao needs a canopy of other
trees around it to survive.

00:18:09.160 --> 00:18:12.890
Cacao survives -- at different
stages of its life cycle,

00:18:12.890 --> 00:18:14.370
it needs different
amounts of light.

00:18:14.370 --> 00:18:16.590
So when it's young ,it
needs a lot of shade.

00:18:16.590 --> 00:18:21.190
As it gets older and bigger, it
needs sort of some less shade,

00:18:21.190 --> 00:18:22.730
but it still needs a canopy.

00:18:22.730 --> 00:18:26.120
It doesn't grow well
in full sun.

00:18:26.120 --> 00:18:28.730
And that's one of the problems
with monocropping and tearing

00:18:28.730 --> 00:18:31.210
down all this land, like
Sam was talking about,

00:18:31.210 --> 00:18:32.720
is the cacao just
doesn't grow as well.

00:18:32.720 --> 00:18:34.610
It doesn't survive
as well there.

00:18:34.610 --> 00:18:38.340
You get a lot of
quantity but not quality

00:18:38.340 --> 00:18:40.110
through those practices.

00:18:40.110 --> 00:18:41.410
&gt;&gt; Samuel Carvalho: And
you need to use chemicals

00:18:41.410 --> 00:18:43.560
as well to make it grow.

00:18:43.560 --> 00:18:44.860
&gt;&gt; Matthew Dixon: Yeah.

00:18:44.860 --> 00:18:47.340
Because without the other
biodiversity around,

00:18:47.340 --> 00:18:48.920
the soil is depleted.

00:18:48.920 --> 00:18:51.900
And the only way to
continue growing the cacao is

00:18:51.900 --> 00:18:53.200
to fertilize it.

00:18:53.200 --> 00:18:55.750
And that's not a great
practice and it's expensive

00:18:55.750 --> 00:18:59.490
for the farmers and they're
already struggling to survive.

00:18:59.490 --> 00:19:04.130
So helping build
agroforestry means

00:19:04.130 --> 00:19:06.440
that it's a little more upkeep

00:19:06.440 --> 00:19:09.080
because you're growing
biodiverse plants,

00:19:09.080 --> 00:19:10.670
but it's less fertilizing.

00:19:10.670 --> 00:19:14.300
And after basically once the
system gets started and gets

00:19:14.300 --> 00:19:17.380
in place and the life cycle
starts repeating itself,

00:19:17.380 --> 00:19:19.680
it gets easier and
easier to care for,

00:19:19.680 --> 00:19:22.740
because nature just
does it all on its own.

00:19:22.740 --> 00:19:26.260
And then, of course, the
socio and economic practices,

00:19:26.260 --> 00:19:28.390
which is making sure
that the laborer is fair,

00:19:28.390 --> 00:19:30.920
the labor is good, people
aren't being mistreated

00:19:30.920 --> 00:19:33.590
and everyone's getting
paid a living wage.

00:19:33.590 --> 00:19:38.220
So this is a close-up
of a cacao clone.

00:19:38.220 --> 00:19:40.350
This is right after it sprouted.

00:19:40.350 --> 00:19:44.620
This is at one of the farms we
work with in Brazil, in Bahia.

00:19:44.620 --> 00:19:46.630
This is Juliana, it's one

00:19:46.630 --> 00:19:50.240
of our really most
intensely-flavored chocolates.

00:19:50.240 --> 00:19:53.910
It has a lot of really,
really nice citrus qualities.

00:19:53.910 --> 00:19:57.160
It's a beautiful, beautiful
bean that they grow there.

00:19:57.160 --> 00:20:01.530
And so basically those
clones are taken care

00:20:01.530 --> 00:20:05.330
of until they reach a mature
stage and they're planted.

00:20:05.330 --> 00:20:09.280
This is kind of a view of the
workers in the clone facility.

00:20:09.280 --> 00:20:12.810
You can see, there's probably
hundreds of these clones

00:20:12.810 --> 00:20:16.920
that they grow and
plant every year.

00:20:16.920 --> 00:20:20.760
This is more of harvest,
harvesting.

00:20:20.760 --> 00:20:22.250
Again, Juliana.

00:20:22.250 --> 00:20:25.330
You can see some of the
pods, they start sort

00:20:25.330 --> 00:20:27.370
of that green color, that's
when they're very young.

00:20:27.370 --> 00:20:30.110
And they become more
yellow and turn to some

00:20:30.110 --> 00:20:31.520
of the brighter vibrant colors

00:20:31.520 --> 00:20:33.860
that you see as they
become ripe.

00:20:35.580 --> 00:20:38.490
There's some ripe
pods on the tree.

00:20:40.190 --> 00:20:41.580
This is more of the harvesting.

00:20:41.580 --> 00:20:45.430
And so here you can see that
when they come out of the pods,

00:20:45.430 --> 00:20:47.750
they're covered in
this white pulp.

00:20:47.750 --> 00:20:52.480
That pulp kind of tastes
like a sour fruit smoothie.

00:20:52.480 --> 00:20:56.700
It's a really wonderful
and interesting flavor.

00:20:56.700 --> 00:21:00.860
And part of the process of cocoa
which makes it so complicated

00:21:00.860 --> 00:21:04.580
on both ends of producing
chocolate is once it's harvested

00:21:04.580 --> 00:21:06.530
and pulled from those
pods, it has to be brought

00:21:06.530 --> 00:21:10.220
to fermentation very
quickly or it rots.

00:21:10.220 --> 00:21:13.620
So we have some pictures.

00:21:13.620 --> 00:21:15.670
This is the Dominican Republic.

00:21:15.670 --> 00:21:19.670
This statue is in San
Francisco de Macoris.

00:21:19.670 --> 00:21:24.380
It's one of the areas where a
lot of high cocoa production is

00:21:24.380 --> 00:21:26.120
in the Dominican Republic.

00:21:26.120 --> 00:21:30.800
And just like Brazil, cocoa is
a major part of the economy.

00:21:30.800 --> 00:21:36.780
It was one of like the only like
staple crops in those regions

00:21:36.780 --> 00:21:38.770
and everybody grows it.

00:21:38.770 --> 00:21:42.110
People are growing it, like Sam
mentioned, in their backyards.

00:21:42.110 --> 00:21:45.750
And a lot of how people
make money there is

00:21:45.750 --> 00:21:47.050
through the cooperatives.

00:21:47.050 --> 00:21:49.110
So people that grow it in their
backyards, they harvest it,

00:21:49.110 --> 00:21:52.430
they bring it to a cooperative,
that cooperative ferments it,

00:21:52.430 --> 00:21:56.040
dries it, and then sells it
under the cooperative's name.

00:21:56.040 --> 00:21:58.570
And that's one of the
biggest challenges too

00:21:58.570 --> 00:22:00.590
with improving the cocoa quality

00:22:00.590 --> 00:22:04.290
and improving the working
environment, because sometimes

00:22:04.290 --> 00:22:06.620
in a lot of these
regions there's not --

00:22:06.620 --> 00:22:09.110
you can go to the direct
cooperative and work with them

00:22:09.110 --> 00:22:10.410
and they work with
their farmers,

00:22:10.410 --> 00:22:12.740
but there's not a direct way
to work with all the farmers

00:22:12.740 --> 00:22:16.010
because the cooperative
doesn't necessarily control all

00:22:16.010 --> 00:22:20.390
of their farms and all of where
they source their own cocoa.

00:22:20.390 --> 00:22:24.280
But this statue was built
basically as a representation

00:22:24.280 --> 00:22:28.430
of how important the cocoa
is to the Dominican people

00:22:28.430 --> 00:22:32.900
and how just part of their
history and culture it is.

00:22:32.900 --> 00:22:35.690
This is, again, we
work with another farm

00:22:35.690 --> 00:22:37.740
in the Dominican
called [inaudible].

00:22:37.740 --> 00:22:42.490
They're also a bird conservatory
and a land preserve there.

00:22:42.490 --> 00:22:47.600
And I wish I could remember
the name of this fruit.

00:22:47.600 --> 00:22:48.900
Say again.

00:22:48.900 --> 00:22:50.200
[inaudible] That
sounds familiar.

00:22:50.200 --> 00:22:51.500
It was really good.

00:22:51.500 --> 00:22:53.050
It was very delicious.

00:22:53.050 --> 00:22:54.840
But that was one of the crops

00:22:54.840 --> 00:22:57.660
that was being grown amongst
the cacao there as part

00:22:57.660 --> 00:23:01.540
of the biodiversity
and the agroforestry.

00:23:01.540 --> 00:23:03.960
There, this is more harvesting.

00:23:03.960 --> 00:23:06.420
Again, you see the white pulp.

00:23:06.420 --> 00:23:07.870
Everything is put
in these buckets

00:23:07.870 --> 00:23:10.510
and then it's transported
by hand further

00:23:10.510 --> 00:23:12.670
down to the fermenter.

00:23:12.670 --> 00:23:16.000
And I think, yeah,
there's a close-up shot.

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:18.410
This is, you can see the
pulp, you can see the beans.

00:23:18.410 --> 00:23:20.880
They're kind of purple
on the inside.

00:23:21.940 --> 00:23:23.820
This is a fermentation center.

00:23:23.820 --> 00:23:28.260
So to cacao is fermented
in these large cedar boxes.

00:23:28.260 --> 00:23:31.190
Basically that takes
four days to a week.

00:23:31.190 --> 00:23:34.470
And throughout that process,
it is turned from box to box.

00:23:34.470 --> 00:23:38.220
It's moved over from box to
box to kind of aerate it,

00:23:38.220 --> 00:23:39.820
to keep everything circulated

00:23:39.820 --> 00:23:41.420
and to keep everything
well mixed together.

00:23:41.420 --> 00:23:45.770
If it's left in one box for
too long, it'll create layers

00:23:45.770 --> 00:23:47.410
and it will ferment unevenly.

00:23:47.410 --> 00:23:50.720
And so that's another
-- as Sam was saying,

00:23:50.720 --> 00:23:54.840
that's another huge part of
cacao quality and it's one

00:23:54.840 --> 00:23:58.470
of the most difficult parts
and least understood part.

00:23:58.470 --> 00:24:01.290
Historically it was
fermented in heaps just piled

00:24:01.290 --> 00:24:04.960
up on the ground and
covered with banana leaves

00:24:04.960 --> 00:24:07.080
and then dried in the sun.

00:24:07.080 --> 00:24:10.190
Which if you're in a humid
tropical environment, is really,

00:24:10.190 --> 00:24:14.100
really difficult, because
it doesn't dry and it molds

00:24:14.100 --> 00:24:16.430
and you lose product,
you lose crop.

00:24:16.430 --> 00:24:20.620
So that was, again, one of those
big innovations that's been

00:24:20.620 --> 00:24:25.150
building for many, many, many
years is fermenting inside

00:24:25.150 --> 00:24:28.510
of a building and
drying in a covered area

00:24:28.510 --> 00:24:32.170
out of lower altitude
out of the mountains

00:24:32.170 --> 00:24:37.720
where the cacao is grown
and in a drier climate.

00:24:37.720 --> 00:24:39.740
That's a close-up
of the fermentation.

00:24:39.740 --> 00:24:41.420
They're typically
covered in banana leaves

00:24:41.420 --> 00:24:44.990
or burlap sacks to
keep the heat in.

00:24:47.510 --> 00:24:50.150
And this is outside of the farm.

00:24:50.150 --> 00:24:59.100
This is an abandoned cacao
drying bed that, again,

00:24:59.100 --> 00:25:02.370
it shows you how important
cacao was to the people

00:25:02.370 --> 00:25:04.140
and to the native economy.

00:25:04.140 --> 00:25:05.770
People did this in
their backyards.

00:25:05.770 --> 00:25:07.670
This was somebody's
home where they grew

00:25:07.670 --> 00:25:10.780
and dried their own cacao
before bringing it to market.

00:25:10.780 --> 00:25:15.950
And these beds worked that
that roof is on a rail.

00:25:15.950 --> 00:25:17.550
So this is actually
when you slide

00:25:17.550 --> 00:25:18.980
that back, it exposes the bed.

00:25:18.980 --> 00:25:22.540
And that was because of the rain
and the humidity in that area

00:25:22.540 --> 00:25:26.150
up in the mountains, they had
to find a way to cover it.

00:25:26.150 --> 00:25:28.450
And basically once the
cooperatives got bigger

00:25:28.450 --> 00:25:32.400
and bigger and started
taking that process away

00:25:32.400 --> 00:25:35.820
from people having to do it at
home, it made it a lot easier

00:25:35.820 --> 00:25:39.740
for people to bring the
cacao to the cooperatives

00:25:39.740 --> 00:25:42.360
and get a better
price because they cut

00:25:42.360 --> 00:25:43.660
down on their own labor.

00:25:43.660 --> 00:25:45.690
They didn't have to spend
all their time fermenting

00:25:45.690 --> 00:25:48.390
and drying it themselves
and this process

00:25:48.390 --> 00:25:51.400
and these beds were abandoned.

00:25:51.400 --> 00:25:56.500
And this is a modernized
drying facility.

00:25:56.500 --> 00:25:58.430
Again, this is all part
of Rosol [phonetic],

00:25:58.430 --> 00:25:59.770
which is in Duarte,
in Dominican.

00:25:59.770 --> 00:26:03.930
And that's the second phase
of the drying process.

00:26:03.930 --> 00:26:07.570
It's dried initially on
those long raised beds,

00:26:07.570 --> 00:26:08.870
which are perforated.

00:26:08.870 --> 00:26:11.610
They're open in the top and
the bottom so air circulates.

00:26:11.610 --> 00:26:14.770
And then the final drying,
they're spread out evenly

00:26:14.770 --> 00:26:17.580
on just the cement
floor, and it is very hot

00:26:17.580 --> 00:26:20.430
and it really finishes
the final dry.

00:26:21.770 --> 00:26:25.290
This is Rosol's hand-sorting
process.

00:26:25.290 --> 00:26:28.830
Every single bean is pulled
off of that cement floor,

00:26:28.830 --> 00:26:33.050
spread out on this table,
it's hand-sorted for hours

00:26:33.050 --> 00:26:38.050
by their workers, and then
bagged and shipped to us.

00:26:38.050 --> 00:26:40.730
This is, again, another view
of the hand-sorting process

00:26:40.730 --> 00:26:44.150
at their fermentation facility.

00:26:44.150 --> 00:26:47.510
This is getting bags
from the hand-sorting

00:26:47.510 --> 00:26:49.820
to where it's actually
loaded for delivery.

00:26:49.820 --> 00:26:53.850
And it's commonly
carried like this.

00:26:55.290 --> 00:26:57.380
And then once we get it,
we make it into chocolate,

00:26:57.380 --> 00:27:03.640
we mold it into bars, and
we package it here in DC.

00:27:03.640 --> 00:27:07.200
And that'll bring us
back to the beginning.

00:27:07.200 --> 00:27:10.510
I think we were going to
open up the discussion

00:27:10.510 --> 00:27:14.020
for some questions if you
guys want to ask us anything

00:27:14.020 --> 00:27:19.560
about cacao and about Brazil
or Dominican Republic and sort

00:27:19.560 --> 00:27:23.000
of us and what else we do.

00:27:25.110 --> 00:27:27.450
&gt;&gt; At the beginning
of your slideshow,

00:27:27.450 --> 00:27:31.900
it seemed like the
plants are being grown

00:27:31.900 --> 00:27:33.990
under tree [inaudible] tents.

00:27:33.990 --> 00:27:35.740
Is that true?

00:27:35.740 --> 00:27:39.160
Just like tobacco in the
Connecticut River Valley.

00:27:39.160 --> 00:27:41.980
So under [inaudible] tents
rather than shade tree?

00:27:41.980 --> 00:27:44.810
The tents I guess
are more adaptable

00:27:44.810 --> 00:27:49.460
because you can put them
there or take them away.

00:27:49.460 --> 00:27:50.760
&gt;&gt; Matthew Dixon: Yeah.

00:27:50.760 --> 00:27:53.430
And that's usually initially
done in the cloning process

00:27:53.430 --> 00:27:56.780
so that the trees can reach a
certain maturity before they're

00:27:56.780 --> 00:28:01.150
actually planted in the
normal growing environment.

00:28:01.150 --> 00:28:04.520
So that's a temporary
holdover and it's much --

00:28:04.520 --> 00:28:05.820
exactly for the reasons
you said.

00:28:05.820 --> 00:28:07.120
It's much more mobile.

00:28:07.120 --> 00:28:09.880
It's much more easy to
construct that than it is to try

00:28:09.880 --> 00:28:13.140
and plant a clone in a shaded
area and then pull it up

00:28:13.140 --> 00:28:17.720
and replant it at the
main growing area.

00:28:17.720 --> 00:28:19.020
Yeah.

00:28:19.020 --> 00:28:23.080
&gt;&gt; So what's the
full life cycle?

00:28:23.080 --> 00:28:28.070
So from clone to harvest,
like what is that time frame?

00:28:28.070 --> 00:28:30.360
How long does that take?

00:28:30.360 --> 00:28:33.200
&gt;&gt; Matthew Dixon: So cacao has
two main harvests every year,

00:28:33.200 --> 00:28:37.640
one in the like late
winter/early spring

00:28:37.640 --> 00:28:40.520
and one in early fall.

00:28:40.520 --> 00:28:44.680
&gt;&gt; Samuel Carvalho:
In the south, yeah.

00:28:44.680 --> 00:28:48.230
&gt;&gt; Matthew Dixon: And
the whole life cycle,

00:28:48.230 --> 00:28:54.820
it takes about five years to
actually receive a full harvest.

00:28:54.820 --> 00:28:57.560
Part of -- and I didn't
have any great pictures

00:28:57.560 --> 00:28:58.860
of it in the slideshow.

00:28:58.860 --> 00:29:02.570
One of the many challenges of
growing cacao is the flower

00:29:02.570 --> 00:29:05.410
that actually grows
the pod is very tiny.

00:29:05.410 --> 00:29:07.790
It's about this big.

00:29:07.790 --> 00:29:11.810
Some cacao is self-pollinating,
which is great,

00:29:11.810 --> 00:29:13.240
but a lot of it isn't.

00:29:13.240 --> 00:29:15.960
And that's part of why the
biodiversity and the lack of use

00:29:15.960 --> 00:29:19.480
of fertilizers and pesticide
chemicals is huge for it,

00:29:19.480 --> 00:29:22.530
because it has to be
pollinated by a midge fly,

00:29:22.530 --> 00:29:25.530
or hand-pollinated, which
is extremely difficult

00:29:25.530 --> 00:29:27.850
because the flowers are so tiny.

00:29:27.850 --> 00:29:32.390
And so from pollination, it
takes about two to three months

00:29:32.390 --> 00:29:36.520
for the pods to actually fully
enlarge, and then another month

00:29:36.520 --> 00:29:38.150
or two for them to mature.

00:29:38.150 --> 00:29:41.310
And most farms sort
of harvest on a cycle.

00:29:41.310 --> 00:29:45.020
They kind of walk around the
farm when harvest season comes

00:29:45.020 --> 00:29:48.010
around and they'll pull pods
down as they become ripe,

00:29:48.010 --> 00:29:50.400
and then come back around
and get the next round

00:29:50.400 --> 00:29:52.050
and so on and so forth.

00:29:52.050 --> 00:29:55.050
But it takes, yeah, it
takes five years for a clone

00:29:55.050 --> 00:29:59.890
to reach enough maturity to
produce a full set of pods

00:29:59.890 --> 00:30:02.530
and then fully developed pods.

00:30:02.530 --> 00:30:03.910
&gt;&gt; And then the other
things that are being grown

00:30:03.910 --> 00:30:06.960
around them, those are
also being harvested

00:30:06.960 --> 00:30:08.820
as well, or those are?

00:30:08.820 --> 00:30:10.220
&gt;&gt; Samuel Carvalho:
Sometimes they're harvested.

00:30:10.220 --> 00:30:15.230
But I think the main concern
actually about this system,

00:30:15.230 --> 00:30:17.130
they just let it
fall in the soil.

00:30:17.130 --> 00:30:20.660
This is going to
provide a more rich.

00:30:20.660 --> 00:30:23.330
You have more nutrients
in the soil as well.

00:30:23.330 --> 00:30:25.440
There is not much
concern about it.

00:30:25.440 --> 00:30:30.860
So in terms of prediction wise,
they don't really [inaudible].

00:30:30.860 --> 00:30:35.140
Also it depends on the system.

00:30:35.140 --> 00:30:37.050
We have so many different
systems.

