00:38:13.850 --> 00:38:16.040
they do fair trade or whatever.

00:38:16.040 --> 00:38:20.010
But when you see the
ingredients, you're going

00:38:20.010 --> 00:38:24.460
to see it listed:
vanilla and soy.

00:38:24.460 --> 00:38:28.980
Which is okay but you need to
ask yourself, why do they use

00:38:28.980 --> 00:38:32.120
that and we do not use that?

00:38:32.120 --> 00:38:35.020
So what's the reason
why they use that?

00:38:35.020 --> 00:38:37.750
So Matt went to the
Culinary Institute,

00:38:37.750 --> 00:38:40.050
so he can give maybe
more in a second.

00:38:40.050 --> 00:38:41.350
&gt;&gt; Matthew Dixon: Yeah.

00:38:41.350 --> 00:38:42.650
Well, it's an indication.

00:38:42.650 --> 00:38:44.730
And that's one of the things
that we, without trying

00:38:44.730 --> 00:38:49.840
to be too militant about
it, try to educate people

00:38:49.840 --> 00:38:52.260
to definitely whenever
you're buying any product,

00:38:52.260 --> 00:38:53.560
to read your labels.

00:38:53.560 --> 00:38:57.410
And if you see soy, if you
see soy lecithin or lecithin

00:38:57.410 --> 00:38:59.550
of any kind, it's an emulsifier.

00:38:59.550 --> 00:39:02.700
And if you see also
there's a wax

00:39:02.700 --> 00:39:04.450
that I'm not remembering
the name

00:39:04.450 --> 00:39:06.570
of that's commonly in there.

00:39:06.570 --> 00:39:07.870
Yeah, yes.

00:39:07.870 --> 00:39:11.010
So those two things are an
indication that regardless

00:39:11.010 --> 00:39:12.820
of whatever else
that package says,

00:39:12.820 --> 00:39:15.090
it's probably being
mass-produced.

00:39:15.090 --> 00:39:18.290
It's probably not exactly
what it says it is.

00:39:18.290 --> 00:39:21.230
There's a lot of
green-washing in products today

00:39:21.230 --> 00:39:23.880
because it's very popular
for things to be non-GMO

00:39:23.880 --> 00:39:26.980
and gluten-free and
all this stuff.

00:39:26.980 --> 00:39:28.350
And so you see a lot of that.

00:39:28.350 --> 00:39:31.230
You go into Whole Foods and you
look in the chocolate aisle,

00:39:31.230 --> 00:39:32.980
you'll see walls and
walls and walls of stuff

00:39:32.980 --> 00:39:35.900
that says it's fair
trade and gluten-free.

00:39:35.900 --> 00:39:37.410
And Chocolate's gluten-free
anyway,

00:39:37.410 --> 00:39:40.800
why would there be
gluten in chocolate?

00:39:40.800 --> 00:39:42.110
You know, [inaudible] yeah.

00:39:42.110 --> 00:39:46.640
And they'll say it's stone
ground and hand-selected.

00:39:46.640 --> 00:39:48.160
And then you look
at the back of it

00:39:48.160 --> 00:39:50.030
and it will generally the
ingredients list will be

00:39:50.030 --> 00:39:51.750
something like chocolate
liquor --

00:39:51.750 --> 00:39:53.110
which means they're
not using beans.

00:39:53.110 --> 00:39:55.750
Which means they're
probably not producing it.

00:39:55.750 --> 00:39:58.460
Chocolate liquor is a
mass-produced chocolate product

00:39:58.460 --> 00:39:59.980
that usually comes
from other companies

00:39:59.980 --> 00:40:01.960
that are buying bulk chocolate.

00:40:01.960 --> 00:40:03.260
And maybe it's fair trade

00:40:03.260 --> 00:40:05.200
because they paid a
little bit more for that,

00:40:05.200 --> 00:40:07.690
but that's not the
same as direct trade.

00:40:07.690 --> 00:40:11.140
And then you'll see soy lecithin

00:40:11.140 --> 00:40:12.440
and you'll see these
other things,

00:40:12.440 --> 00:40:15.030
and that's a huge
indication that this is not --

00:40:15.030 --> 00:40:16.740
the product's kind
of lying to you.

00:40:16.740 --> 00:40:23.130
And then especially if
it costs less than $5,

00:40:23.130 --> 00:40:26.350
that's probably another
huge indication

00:40:26.350 --> 00:40:28.920
that something is wrong
in their supply chain.

00:40:28.920 --> 00:40:32.310
Somewhere along the line
someone, probably someone

00:40:32.310 --> 00:40:34.230
who produced the cocoa,
is not getting paid,

00:40:34.230 --> 00:40:37.170
or they're buying it already
made from somewhere else

00:40:37.170 --> 00:40:39.720
with a lot of fillers
and, you know,

00:40:39.720 --> 00:40:42.040
substrate ingredients
to cut the cost.

00:40:42.040 --> 00:40:44.960
Because right now it's
just it's not possible

00:40:44.960 --> 00:40:48.010
to produce high-quality
chocolate

00:40:48.010 --> 00:40:53.530
that you paid direct trade like
living wages to the farmers

00:40:53.530 --> 00:40:58.420
without charging $7-$8
for the end product.

00:40:58.420 --> 00:41:00.470
Because just it's
very expensive,

00:41:00.470 --> 00:41:03.050
and shipping logistics and
like everything that goes

00:41:03.050 --> 00:41:06.760
into getting that product
here and then making it

00:41:06.760 --> 00:41:08.420
and then going from there.

00:41:08.420 --> 00:41:10.810
So that's one of the things that
I always try and tell people,

00:41:10.810 --> 00:41:13.680
if you see a chocolate
bar and it's $5 or less,

00:41:13.680 --> 00:41:15.870
there's something wrong.

00:41:15.870 --> 00:41:22.160
I encourage you not to buy that.

00:41:22.160 --> 00:41:23.970
&gt;&gt; I'm curious, from the time --

00:41:23.970 --> 00:41:26.740
so a tree is producing
in five years.

00:41:26.740 --> 00:41:28.590
What's the longevity of a tree?

00:41:28.590 --> 00:41:30.130
How long does it produce?

00:41:30.130 --> 00:41:31.430
&gt;&gt; Matthew Dixon: How
long does it produce for?

00:41:31.430 --> 00:41:32.730
Yeah, man.

00:41:32.730 --> 00:41:34.940
&gt;&gt; In optimal conditions.

00:41:34.940 --> 00:41:36.500
&gt;&gt; Matthew Dixon: Yeah,
in optimal conditions,

00:41:36.500 --> 00:41:38.400
I think you get 10 years.

00:41:38.400 --> 00:41:43.010
They'll produce sort of at --
they'll produce forever as long

00:41:43.010 --> 00:41:45.870
as you maintain the tree
and nothing happens to it,

00:41:45.870 --> 00:41:47.560
they don't get any diseases.

00:41:47.560 --> 00:41:50.320
But after I believe
it's 10 years,

00:41:50.320 --> 00:41:53.350
you start to see a
significant drop in the quantity

00:41:53.350 --> 00:41:55.730
of pods the tree
is able to produce.

00:41:55.730 --> 00:41:58.790
And then also the quality
will start to falter

00:41:58.790 --> 00:42:01.260
as the trees get older.

00:42:01.260 --> 00:42:04.010
And one of the things
that we saw at the farms

00:42:04.010 --> 00:42:05.310
in the Dominican at least

00:42:05.310 --> 00:42:07.450
that they were doing is
they started grafting.

00:42:07.450 --> 00:42:11.790
After the trees hit that like
sort of beyond maturity point,

00:42:11.790 --> 00:42:13.160
they would start to graph them.

00:42:13.160 --> 00:42:15.860
And so they would take
one of those new clones

00:42:15.860 --> 00:42:17.160
that you guys saw
on the pictures

00:42:17.160 --> 00:42:21.100
and they would actually graft it
to the rootstock of an old tree.

00:42:21.100 --> 00:42:23.480
And then once that
clone reached maturity

00:42:23.480 --> 00:42:26.690
on the older trees rootstock,
they'd cut the older tree down

00:42:26.690 --> 00:42:28.160
and allow it to keep
growing that way.

00:42:28.160 --> 00:42:34.900
And I think I was told that that
could only be done I think twice

00:42:34.900 --> 00:42:38.700
or maybe three times before the
rootstock would also get too

00:42:38.700 --> 00:42:43.490
worn out to maintain
the new growth.

00:42:43.490 --> 00:42:46.130
So yeah, it's definitely
a difficult rotation

00:42:46.130 --> 00:42:49.610
for those farms once the
trees start maturing as well.

00:42:49.610 --> 00:42:51.970
But one of the things happening
right now is those farms are

00:42:51.970 --> 00:42:55.560
planting so many new clones
and there's so much new growth,

00:42:55.560 --> 00:42:57.040
they'll be sustainable

00:42:57.040 --> 00:42:59.790
for a good long time before
they start encountering

00:42:59.790 --> 00:43:01.580
those problem.

00:43:01.580 --> 00:43:02.880
&gt;&gt; Samuel Carvalho:
There is also

00:43:02.880 --> 00:43:06.390
like a misconception sometimes
people say that chocolate has

00:43:06.390 --> 00:43:08.910
to be -- dark chocolate
is bitter.

00:43:08.910 --> 00:43:12.610
And it doesn't have
to be bitter.

00:43:12.610 --> 00:43:15.550
That's, again, I'm
talking about the soy

00:43:15.550 --> 00:43:21.430
and like all those
ingredients in chocolate.

00:43:21.430 --> 00:43:25.490
Because cacao beans itself
is just -- a raw cacao bean,

00:43:25.490 --> 00:43:28.810
if you crack it, if you just
chew it, it doesn't taste good.

00:43:28.810 --> 00:43:30.910
It's kind of -- it's really bad.

00:43:30.910 --> 00:43:33.050
I had someone try
to do it before,

00:43:33.050 --> 00:43:35.160
and the pulp is very good.

00:43:35.160 --> 00:43:38.730
But inside, it's not
pleasant, it's not enjoyable.

00:43:38.730 --> 00:43:42.670
But you have the chocolate, you
know, so that's why you need

00:43:42.670 --> 00:43:45.170
to have a very good
fermentation process,

00:43:45.170 --> 00:43:46.470
all these processes
that you saw here.

00:43:46.470 --> 00:43:50.530
It has to be like in
shape so you're going

00:43:50.530 --> 00:43:52.220
to have much more quality,

00:43:52.220 --> 00:43:55.150
much better flavors
and everything else.

00:43:55.150 --> 00:43:56.450
&gt;&gt; Matthew Dixon: Yeah.

00:43:56.450 --> 00:43:59.320
And that's sort of our
responsibility to take that --

00:43:59.320 --> 00:44:02.680
take all that hard work and
beautiful work that the farmers

00:44:02.680 --> 00:44:06.410
and the people did and make
sure that we're honoring that

00:44:06.410 --> 00:44:11.210
and we're displaying like the
full effort and like the full,

00:44:11.210 --> 00:44:13.730
you know, beauty of the
thing that they did.

00:44:13.730 --> 00:44:17.780
Yeah. And that's what's the
challenge that's kind of fun

00:44:17.780 --> 00:44:20.290
and exciting on our end is
to get that in and say, okay,

00:44:20.290 --> 00:44:23.920
this has a lot of lemon flavor
and kind of some raisin flavor,

00:44:23.920 --> 00:44:25.220
how do we bring that out?

00:44:25.220 --> 00:44:26.690
How do we keep it from
getting really bitter

00:44:26.690 --> 00:44:29.650
and make this pleasant and
bring out those flavors?

00:44:29.650 --> 00:44:31.600
Yeah, and that's
one of the things

00:44:31.600 --> 00:44:32.900
that we work really hard to do.

00:44:32.900 --> 00:44:34.200
&gt;&gt; Samuel Carvalho: And even

00:44:34.200 --> 00:44:37.350
if you get a really bad
cacao beans, of course,

00:44:37.350 --> 00:44:40.660
you have the whole process,
you try to make the chocolate

00:44:40.660 --> 00:44:45.640
and I guess the best
as possible.

00:44:45.640 --> 00:44:48.070
But sometimes when you get
a really bad cacao beans

00:44:48.070 --> 00:44:52.590
and you get a lot of samples
from like all over and we try

00:44:52.590 --> 00:44:55.710
and try to change
the [inaudible]

00:44:55.710 --> 00:44:58.510
or change the roast
method, whatever you do,

00:44:58.510 --> 00:45:00.480
the quality is not
going to be good.

00:45:00.480 --> 00:45:03.670
So, okay, but it has
to pleasant for people,

00:45:03.670 --> 00:45:05.350
otherwise nobody's
going to buy this.

00:45:05.350 --> 00:45:06.650
So what are we going to do?

00:45:06.650 --> 00:45:08.660
Okay, let's put some soy in
it and vanilla, you know.

00:45:08.660 --> 00:45:11.480
So that's why --
it's much easier,

00:45:11.480 --> 00:45:14.040
but it's much more unpleasant.

00:45:14.040 --> 00:45:15.870
&gt;&gt; Matthew Dixon: And that's
probably why it's important

00:45:15.870 --> 00:45:18.090
for us and other
chocolate makers

00:45:18.090 --> 00:45:20.730
to have a relationship
with our farmers.

00:45:20.730 --> 00:45:23.340
Because we can go back to
them and we can say, hey,

00:45:23.340 --> 00:45:26.990
you sent us this really
great sample, there is a lot

00:45:26.990 --> 00:45:30.590
of potential here, but we
think your fermentation needs

00:45:30.590 --> 00:45:31.890
your work.

00:45:31.890 --> 00:45:34.380
And we can kind of help
facilitate them getting in touch

00:45:34.380 --> 00:45:37.410
with someone that can help
them improve their processes

00:45:37.410 --> 00:45:40.560
so that they can continue
to sell their market --

00:45:40.560 --> 00:45:44.200
their cocoa to a market
like ours and get more money

00:45:44.200 --> 00:45:47.050
for it and, you know,
build their product

00:45:47.050 --> 00:45:50.270
and their own economy.

00:45:50.270 --> 00:45:53.720
Again, that's why, you know,
we try to sort of encourage,

00:45:53.720 --> 00:45:55.760
like look for craft
chocolate, look for people

00:45:55.760 --> 00:45:57.470
that are transparent,
look for, you know --

00:45:57.470 --> 00:46:00.160
there's other makers not
just us in the country

00:46:00.160 --> 00:46:03.370
that are doing these things and
are committed to these things.

00:46:03.370 --> 00:46:06.220
Because that's really what's
going to make chocolate last

00:46:06.220 --> 00:46:08.780
and what's really going to,
you know, improve the lives

00:46:08.780 --> 00:46:14.160
of the people in the
regions that it comes from.

00:46:14.160 --> 00:46:15.460
&gt;&gt; Just one more question.

