00:48:10.100 --> 00:48:14.130
look, this is your
product, this is your beans.

00:48:14.130 --> 00:48:19.360
And people don't like it,
and it's really funny.

00:48:19.360 --> 00:48:23.310
But yeah, I think if you're
in a cocoa-producing region,

00:48:23.310 --> 00:48:27.060
I would say, you know,
you're probably safe,

00:48:27.060 --> 00:48:31.920
it just might not be what
we would expect it to taste

00:48:31.920 --> 00:48:35.270
like with our own palettes and
our own sort of taste coming

00:48:35.270 --> 00:48:38.090
from Cadbury and Hershey's
and things that we've grown

00:48:38.090 --> 00:48:39.710
up recognizing as chocolate.

00:48:39.710 --> 00:48:44.490
&gt;&gt; Samuel Carvalho: They might
have a very good cacao bean,

00:48:44.490 --> 00:48:46.430
but we have all the process

00:48:46.430 --> 00:48:49.730
to make this much
more like enjoyable.

00:48:49.730 --> 00:48:54.710
So, for example, just
very briefly our process.

00:48:54.710 --> 00:48:57.270
We classify the beans
when we get it,

00:48:57.270 --> 00:48:59.390
is how the beans enter
the fermentation process,

00:48:59.390 --> 00:49:01.020
dry fermented.

00:49:01.020 --> 00:49:04.160
We classify just try to
make sure there is no rocks

00:49:04.160 --> 00:49:06.410
or heavy metals or
something like that

00:49:06.410 --> 00:49:09.720
on the production line.

00:49:09.720 --> 00:49:11.980
And then we just get
all the beans roasted

00:49:11.980 --> 00:49:14.420
and then just reduce
the moisture pretty much

00:49:14.420 --> 00:49:15.720
in the roasting process.

00:49:15.720 --> 00:49:17.380
&gt;&gt; Matthew Dixon: And the
roasting process develops the

00:49:17.380 --> 00:49:20.580
actual flavors of chocolate,
like Sam was saying earlier.

00:49:20.580 --> 00:49:24.120
So yeah. So when we
get the beans in,

00:49:24.120 --> 00:49:27.400
there's all this potential
in this neat little package.

00:49:27.400 --> 00:49:30.980
And we as a chocolate
maker have to figure

00:49:30.980 --> 00:49:32.280
out how we're going to roast it.

00:49:32.280 --> 00:49:34.940
Because the roast profile
distinctly changes the flavors.

00:49:34.940 --> 00:49:37.890
It drives off all kinds of
volatile compounds and sort

00:49:37.890 --> 00:49:40.290
of develops the chocolate
flavor.

00:49:40.290 --> 00:49:41.960
And just like in coffee,

00:49:41.960 --> 00:49:46.300
you'll find lighter roasts can
be more acidic and more intense

00:49:46.300 --> 00:49:48.680
and sometimes bitter
and not pleasant.

00:49:48.680 --> 00:49:51.260
Darker roasts, you start
getting into the more just

00:49:51.260 --> 00:49:53.970
like pure chocolate-y flavors
and you'll start to lose some

00:49:53.970 --> 00:49:56.700
of those more subtle fruit
flavors and that kind of stuff.

00:49:56.700 --> 00:49:58.890
And if you roast too far,
you start getting burnt

00:49:58.890 --> 00:50:02.170
or you start getting like
roasty bitter like burnt toast.

00:50:02.170 --> 00:50:03.470
Where you have really
dark toast,

00:50:03.470 --> 00:50:04.770
you get that kind of bitterness.

00:50:04.770 --> 00:50:08.430
So that's one of
the first challenges

00:50:08.430 --> 00:50:11.280
for us making chocolate
is roasting.

00:50:11.280 --> 00:50:13.660
And we get a bean in and
we sample it and we kind

00:50:13.660 --> 00:50:16.880
of will do experimental roasts
and we'll kind of play with it

00:50:16.880 --> 00:50:20.240
until we get a flavor
profile that we like.

00:50:20.240 --> 00:50:23.370
And then from there it's
actually grinding the chocolate,

00:50:23.370 --> 00:50:25.610
which incorporates
air, is a question

00:50:25.610 --> 00:50:27.230
of how much sugar
we're going to add,

00:50:27.230 --> 00:50:28.890
what kind of sugar
we're going to add.

00:50:28.890 --> 00:50:30.750
Because that contributes
to the flavoring.

00:50:30.750 --> 00:50:34.290
If you use like a
white like plane

00:50:34.290 --> 00:50:36.940
like fully extracted
sugar, if you something more

00:50:36.940 --> 00:50:39.840
like a raw sugar that
has a lot of the molasses

00:50:39.840 --> 00:50:42.780
and like cane flavor
still in it.

00:50:42.780 --> 00:50:44.930
There is a really
interesting maker in Wisconsin

00:50:44.930 --> 00:50:47.780
that was using rice
sugar in his chocolate,

00:50:47.780 --> 00:50:51.980
which had a really unique
flavor, really interesting.

00:50:51.980 --> 00:50:54.350
But there's so much
with chocolate.

00:50:54.350 --> 00:50:58.190
And that's one of the things
that we try to do is we try

00:50:58.190 --> 00:51:01.840
and balance that act between
like making chocolate that's

00:51:01.840 --> 00:51:05.040
really interesting flavor to
making chocolate that's pleasant

00:51:05.040 --> 00:51:10.000
and enjoyable for everyone.

