00:55:24.890 --> 00:55:30.060
like nuts and candy and
like other stuff we make

00:55:30.060 --> 00:55:33.140
in-house too.

00:55:33.140 --> 00:55:35.580
But for the most part.

00:55:35.580 --> 00:55:38.480
&gt;&gt; Samuel Carvalho: We do
have milk chocolate as well.

00:55:38.480 --> 00:55:44.720
And we actually have a 57% milk
chocolate, which means 57% cacao

00:55:44.720 --> 00:55:50.050
and milk powder, organic whole
milk powder and organic sugar.

00:55:50.050 --> 00:55:51.500
So those are all
the ingredients.

00:55:51.500 --> 00:55:52.830
So we do add flavors

00:55:52.830 --> 00:55:54.820
and we don't make only
the plain chocolate.

00:55:54.820 --> 00:55:58.220
And we also have special
editions I can show you here,

00:55:58.220 --> 00:56:01.570
and that's great because
-- so, for example,

00:56:01.570 --> 00:56:03.200
this one here, the first one.

00:56:03.200 --> 00:56:05.420
See it? Grapefruit,

00:56:05.420 --> 00:56:09.100
it's grapefruit [inaudible]
oil with [inaudible].

00:56:09.100 --> 00:56:15.440
So it's a very interesting
flavor, thanks to Matt,

00:56:15.440 --> 00:56:18.180
he developed this chocolate bar.

00:56:18.180 --> 00:56:19.750
&gt;&gt; Matthew Dixon: That
one's a lot of fun.

00:56:19.750 --> 00:56:21.050
&gt;&gt; Samuel Carvalho: Yeah.

00:56:21.050 --> 00:56:22.690
It's actually 70%
dark chocolate.

00:56:22.690 --> 00:56:25.550
So it's dark chocolate
with some --

00:56:25.550 --> 00:56:27.600
added those two other
ingredients.

00:56:27.600 --> 00:56:32.300
This one here is a barrel-aged
edition, and that's aged,

00:56:32.300 --> 00:56:34.510
you know, wine barrel
for about six months

00:56:34.510 --> 00:56:37.550
and it gets the flavor.

00:56:37.550 --> 00:56:38.890
The same process.

00:56:38.890 --> 00:56:40.340
&gt;&gt; The dry beans are?

00:56:40.340 --> 00:56:44.140
&gt;&gt; Samuel Carvalho: The cacao
nibs or the dry beans, yes.

00:56:44.140 --> 00:56:45.960
One or the other.

00:56:45.960 --> 00:56:51.290
This one here is the same
process but it's a rye barrel.

00:56:51.290 --> 00:56:52.590
&gt;&gt; Matthew Dixon:
Rye whiskey barrel.

00:56:52.590 --> 00:56:53.890
&gt;&gt; Samuel Carvalho:
Rye whiskey barrel.

00:56:53.890 --> 00:56:57.030
It's actually a local company
that's a winery distributer.

00:56:57.030 --> 00:56:59.290
It's based here in
Washington, DC.

00:56:59.290 --> 00:57:02.030
And it gathers the beans
kind of like a tray

00:57:02.030 --> 00:57:03.870
of the beans -- sorry,
the barrels.

00:57:03.870 --> 00:57:07.260
They give us the barrels after
they empty it out of whiskey.

00:57:07.260 --> 00:57:09.650
We fill up with cacao nibs.

00:57:09.650 --> 00:57:11.800
And after six months, they
get the barrels back and fill

00:57:11.800 --> 00:57:16.780
up with whiskey and it has
chocolate flavor into it.

00:57:16.780 --> 00:57:20.050
So it's a very interesting
process.

00:57:20.050 --> 00:57:21.830
&gt;&gt; Matthew Dixon:
So you were asking

00:57:21.830 --> 00:57:23.130
about what the difference is

00:57:23.130 --> 00:57:24.890
between like milk
and dark chocolate.

00:57:24.890 --> 00:57:29.150
And really, that's one of those
hard things that goes back

00:57:29.150 --> 00:57:32.390
to what we all grew up with,
which is this hard line

00:57:32.390 --> 00:57:34.510
between stuff like Hershey's
-- which is milk chocolate --

00:57:34.510 --> 00:57:37.310
and then what most people
probably recognize dark

00:57:37.310 --> 00:57:38.890
chocolate is like
baking chocolate.

00:57:38.890 --> 00:57:41.860
And it's super bitter, and
it's unpleasant, it's terrible.

00:57:41.860 --> 00:57:47.730
But dark chocolate I think
legally is defined as anything

00:57:47.730 --> 00:57:53.450
that contains cacao over I want
to say 20% actual cacao beans.

00:57:53.450 --> 00:57:58.900
And so technically our milk
chocolate is a dark milk

00:57:58.900 --> 00:58:01.720
chocolate, which is
really fascinating.

00:58:01.720 --> 00:58:05.040
And so what's great about is you
have this great sort of marrying

00:58:05.040 --> 00:58:07.680
of the flavors of the
milk and the creaminess

00:58:07.680 --> 00:58:09.050
and then the fruit flavors

00:58:09.050 --> 00:58:12.490
from the actual cacao
and the chocolate.

00:58:12.490 --> 00:58:16.120
Our milk chocolate bar is
one of my favorite things.

00:58:16.120 --> 00:58:22.180
And then when we're
making our single origin,

00:58:22.180 --> 00:58:23.700
these bars that kind of follow.

00:58:23.700 --> 00:58:25.000
This is the blended bar.

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:28.770
That's the other two beans from
Brazil, I was talking about.

00:58:28.770 --> 00:58:30.250
And our milk chocolate
is actually made

00:58:30.250 --> 00:58:31.570
with the same blend.

00:58:31.570 --> 00:58:34.590
And then after that we have our
single origin dark chocolates,

00:58:34.590 --> 00:58:36.540
which are made with
a single bean

00:58:36.540 --> 00:58:39.590
from a single farm
from a single area.

00:58:39.590 --> 00:58:44.240
And those we don't
specifically aim.

00:58:44.240 --> 00:58:49.160
It's kind of dependent on what
flavors we get in the chocolate

00:58:49.160 --> 00:58:51.360
when -- in the beans, when we
get them in and we taste them.

00:58:51.360 --> 00:58:54.430
Sometimes, like I was saying
earlier, we'll get a bean in

00:58:54.430 --> 00:58:56.440
and we'll say, okay, this
has this really nice sort

00:58:56.440 --> 00:58:57.810
of dark fruit flavors.

00:58:57.810 --> 00:59:00.360
It's kind of raisiny and figgy.

00:59:00.360 --> 00:59:02.060
And let's see if we
can bring that out.

00:59:02.060 --> 00:59:04.060
And that's kind of
what we aim for.

00:59:04.060 --> 00:59:08.100
And keeping that in mind, if
there's something really strange

00:59:08.100 --> 00:59:10.730
in there that we know
people won't like --

00:59:10.730 --> 00:59:12.030
which I think was
your other question.

00:59:12.030 --> 00:59:14.020
Is like do we try and make
chocolate for, you know,

00:59:14.020 --> 00:59:17.710
like flavors that
people are interested in?

00:59:17.710 --> 00:59:19.040
And yes, absolutely.

00:59:19.040 --> 00:59:22.060
Because, you know, I
might really like some

00:59:22.060 --> 00:59:25.500
like weird esoteric like
mushroomy flavor that's

00:59:25.500 --> 00:59:28.270
in some bean that we
get, but I don't know

00:59:28.270 --> 00:59:30.020
that anyone else
wants to eat chocolate

00:59:30.020 --> 00:59:31.480
that tastes like mushrooms.

00:59:31.480 --> 00:59:34.780
So of course we try and kind
of like look at those beans

00:59:34.780 --> 00:59:38.400
and say, okay, like there
is this interesting flavor,

00:59:38.400 --> 00:59:41.100
but maybe that's not going to
be like the most enjoyed flavor,

00:59:41.100 --> 00:59:43.120
so let's not try
to bring that out.

00:59:43.120 --> 00:59:46.440
Like let's try and like guide
it towards these other flavors

00:59:46.440 --> 00:59:49.120
that we think, you
know, people will like.

